{
  "text": "We report a series of patients (N = 12) with biopsy-proven AL amyloidosis who had less than a very good partial response (PR) to bortezomib-based initial therapy (nine had no response (NR) and three PR), and therefore were likely to have inferior overall survival, [CITATION_1] who then underwent SCT with risk-adapted melphalan. The median age was 58 (range, 53-70) and 9 were male. Ten came to us after being treated elsewhere; they did not receive SCT as first-line treatment because of plasma cells 410%, institutional limitations or poor performance status. Two patients diagnosed at our center as eligible for SCT refused our recommendation and chose bortezomib-based therapy instead. Nine patients were treated with bortezomib, cyclophosphamide and dexamethasone, and 3 with bortezomib and dexamethasone, for a median of 4 cycles (2-8). Patients receiving 2 or 3 cycles were switched to SCT because of the risk of organ disease progression due to ineffective therapy as is standard practice. [CITATION_2] Ten patients (83%) had lambda clonal disease. Nine with NR had median involved FLC at diagnosis and post initial therapy (pre-SCT) of 180 (74-648) and 265 mg/L (116-410), while 3 with PR had medians of 2552 (250-9780) and 100 mg/L (98-1620) at those time points respectively. In neither instance were comparisons statistically significant by paired t-test. Six had two organs and six had one organ involved. Seven had cardiac involvement, six stage 2 and one stage 3. Seven had renal involvement, one stage 1, four stage 2 and two stage 3. Two had gastrointestinal involvement.",
  "citation_candidates": [
